      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "4cdc0320679b4ad4",
        "text": "In this period, the closest Robin comes to Alexander-style patterns, I think, is in his ‘ten principles’ of new economy \\[DaO 2009 xxx], each of which is a compact narrative-story of innovative economic practice. I suspect that each of these ten stories might quite easily be translated into a foprop pattern, around a core of altered relations of production (see my exploration of this above, on ‘Pattern language(ing) as a dance of knowing’). As far as I know Robin didn’t extend this collection of story-form descriptions of  ‘principles’ to create a library, and these ten bear a rather arbitrary relationship to the long lists of ‘methods and tools’ (in *The open book of social innovation*, 527 of them) that were developed around the same time.\n\n"
      },
      "after": "2327558910e35864",
